o about 2 mSv (millisieverts) per year. This equates to about one chest X-ray (0.1 mSv) every ten days. Other forms of radiation deliver higher doses.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is responsible for the highest dose of radiation exposure?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT lung for screening","CT coronary angiogram","Contrast-enhanced abdominal CT","Nuclear cardiology stress test","PET/CT"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe following are the approximate radiation doses for each of the listed procedures:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECT lung screening: 3 mSv\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECT coronary angiogram 12 mSv\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESingle phase contrast-enhanced abdominal CT 8 mSv\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMulti-phase abdominal CT 20 mSv\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENuclear cardiology stress test 12 mSv\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPET/CT\u003C/strong\u003E 15-25 mSv\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst these investigations may have considerable advantage in diagnosis and management, with perhaps removal of the need (and risk) of other types of procedures, the risks of radiation exposure and the potential effects of cumulative doses must always be remembered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["PET/CT scans have relatively high radiation exposure.","Understanding radiation doses is important for evaluating the risks and benefits of imaging modalities."],"references":["Kamiya K, Ozasa K, Akiba S, Niwa O, Kodama K, Takamura N, Zaharieva EK, Kimura Y, Wakeford R. Long-term effects of radiation exposure on health. Lancet. 2015 Aug 1;386(9992):469-78. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(15)61167-9. PMID: 26251392. Available from: ht